      Silicon Valley insider trading ring!=E2=80=9CSix Charged in Silicon V=
alley Insider Trading Ring=E2=80=9D is the headline on this Securities and =
Exchange Commission news release. (There is a related criminal case.) It is=
 perhaps less of a Silicon Valley Insider Trading Ring than I had hoped. It=
=E2=80=99s not, like, senior product managers at Facebook and Google and Ap=
ple all tipping each other, but why would it be. Only two of the six people=
 in the ring worked at tech companies. Still it has its charm:According to =
the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint, Nathaniel Brown, who served as the revenue rec=
ognition manager for Infinera Corporation, repeatedly tipped Infinera=E2=80=
=99s unannounced quarterly earnings and financial performance to his best f=
riend, Benjamin Wylam, from April 2016 until Brown left the company in Nove=
mber 2017. =C2=A0The SEC=E2=80=99s complaint alleges that Wylam, a high sch=
ool teacher and bookmaker, traded on this information and also tipped Navee=
n Sood, who owed Wylam a six-figure gambling debt. =C2=A0Sood allegedly tra=
ded on this information and tipped his three friends Marcus Bannon, Matthew=
 Rauch, and Naresh Ramaiya, each of whom also illegally traded on the infor=
mation. =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0=C2=A0The SEC=E2=80=99s complaint furthe=
r alleges that Bannon tipped Sood with material, nonpublic information conc=
erning Bannon=E2=80=99s employer, Fortinet Inc. =C2=A0As alleged in the com=
plaint, Bannon learned in early October 2016 that Fortinet was going to une=
xpectedly announce preliminary negative financial results. =C2=A0Bannon all=
egedly tipped this information to Sood, who used it to trade. =C2=A0After l=
earning the information, Sood allegedly tipped Wylam and Ramaiya, who also =
traded.=E2=80=9CHigh school teacher and bookmaker=E2=80=9D is just an A+ jo=
b description. Also I like that the teacher/bookie allegedly passed some il=
legal inside information on to a guy who owed him money, so the guy could g=
et the money to pay him back: =E2=80=9CSood owed Wylam a six-figure gamblin=
g debt, and Wylam knew that Sood could use profits generated from insider t=
rading to pay off at least part of that debt,=E2=80=9D says the SEC complai=
nt. But then Sood got some inside information of his own and allegedly pass=
ed it back to his bookie/creditor: =E2=80=9CSood also owed Wylam a six-figu=
re gambling debt,=E2=80=9D the complaint repeats,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cand Sood ex=
pected that, in return for providing inside information, Wylam would forgiv=
e a portion of the debt.=E2=80=9D I don=E2=80=99t know, man, I feel like bo=
th of those things can=E2=80=99t be true. If Sood could pay Wyman in inside=
r-trading tips, then he shouldn=E2=80=99t be able to pay him off with money=
 from insider trading on Wyman=E2=80=99s own tips? The whole economy of ins=
ider trading to pay gambling debts is a little murky to me.Also we have=C2=
=A0talked recently about  insider-trading tradecraft. This is =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0not the good tradecraft:On or around July 28, 2016, Wylam sent Brown a s=
creenshot of Wylam=E2=80=99s brokerage account, showing the balance after I=
nfinera=E2=80=99s July 27 announcement, including the profits that Wylam ma=
de purchasing Infinera put options before the announcement. According to Br=
own, he did a =E2=80=9Cdouble-take=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cbecause the number was=
 so big.=E2=80=9DShortly after seeing the screenshot of Wylam=E2=80=99s acc=
ount on July 28, Brown called Wylam on the telephone. During the call, Wyla=
m explained how he made such large profits purchasing Infinera put options =
before the July 27 announcement. Brown =E2=80=9Cflipped out=E2=80=9D becaus=
e, in his view, the massive size of Wylam=E2=80=99s trades and profits rais=
ed an =E2=80=9Cobvious red flag.=E2=80=9DAfter the July 28 call, in order t=
o cover up his role in tipping material nonpublic information to Wylam, Bro=
wn deleted Wylam from his Facebook account and deleted his emails with Wyla=
m. ...On August 5, 2016, Brown=E2=80=94whose tips enabled his friend, Wylam=
, to make nearly one million dollars=E2=80=94texted his then-girlfriend to =
inform her that he was going to Wylam=E2=80=99s house to, among other thing=
s, =E2=80=9Ctalk to him about $.=E2=80=9D One week later, on or around Augu=
st 12, Brown took a photograph of numerous one hundred dollar bills spread =
across his bathroom sink.=C2=A0Yes yes yes if you have never traded options=
 before, buying a ton of put options just before a bad earnings announcemen=
t does raise an obvious red flag, but so does sending your insider buddy a =
screenshot of your profits! So does taking pictures of the pile of hundred-=
dollar bills that you got as a payoff for your insider-trading tip!=C2=A0Fu=
ture receivables insuranceThe more I read about Greensill Capital the more =
impressed I am by the  simple arbitrage it pulled off. The core of it seems=
 to be this:=09Companies want long-term unsecured loans to finance their gr=
owth: It is safer, for a company, to borrow money for a long time, because =
if you run into trouble you don=E2=80=99t have to pay it back. And you=E2=
=80=99d rather borrow without pledging any specific assets.=09Investors wan=
t to put their money into short-term secured loans: It is safer, for an inv=
estor, to lend money for a short time, because you can always get your mone=
y back quickly. And you=E2=80=99d rather lend against specific assets that =
you can seize and sell if anything goes wrong.=09If you can tell companies =
that they=E2=80=99re getting long-term unsecured funding, and tell investor=
s that they=E2=80=99re providing short-term secured funding, then you=E2=80=
=99ve got something.In broad terms that is not a novel or unique business m=
odel. Arguably=C2=A0banking=C2=A0works that way: Banks take deposits (short=
-term loans from investors) and use them to fund long-term loans to compani=
es, so everyone gets what they want;=C2=A0there is a whole apparatus of cap=
ital and prudential regulation to make sure that it mostly works out, and t=
here are decades of theorizing about how it works and how it could work bet=
ter and so forth. And there are various forms of shadow banking that also d=
o this sort of =E2=80=9Cmaturity transformation=E2=80=9D: Investors make sh=
ort-term investments, companies get long-term financing, and some mumbo-jum=
bo occurs in the middle to make everyone feel better about it.But Greensill=
 cut through all of this with a much simpler approach. Greensill=E2=80=99s =
innovation was basically to say: Look, if we use terms like =E2=80=9Csupply=
-chain finance=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Creceivables finance,=E2=80=9D people w=
ill think=C2=A0that we=E2=80=99re doing short-term secured lending because =
that=E2=80=99s what those terms traditionally mean, but we can just do long=
-term unsecured lending instead and everyone will be happy. Specifically:=
=09Greensill loaned money to companies in =E2=80=9Creceivables finance=E2=
=80=9D or =E2=80=9Csupply chain finance=E2=80=9D programs, in which it fina=
nced their accounts receivable (or payable) and got paid back quickly. (Tha=
t is, the company would sell a product to a customer on credit, Greensill w=
ould pay the company today, and the customer would pay Greensill back in a =
month or whatever.) But it also cheerfully financed their =E2=80=9Cprospect=
ive receivables=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cfuture receivables=E2=80=9D: If a comp=
any=C2=A0hoped=C2=A0to=C2=A0one day=C2=A0sell some products to some=C2=A0po=
ssible future customer, Greensill would lend it money against those receiva=
bles too. Since those receivables didn=E2=80=99t exist, those loans would n=
ot be paid back quickly, and Greensill would just roll them over indefinite=
ly. For the company this felt like long-term unsecured financing: Greensill=
 would give it money, it would invest the money in trying to grow its busin=
ess, and eventually if the business grew it would pay back the money.=09Gre=
ensill sold these loans to investors emphasizing the words =E2=80=9Creceiva=
bles finance=E2=80=9D and not so much the words =E2=80=9Cprospective=E2=80=
=9D or =E2=80=9Cfuture.=E2=80=9D Sure sure sure somewhere in the fine print=
  maybe it mentioned that some of the receivables might not exist yet, but =
you put =E2=80=9Csupply-chain finance=E2=80=9D on the cover and sell the lo=
ans to money-market-ish funds and nobody really notices.=09Everyone is happ=
y.Nobody is happy now, of course;  with Greensill=E2=80=99s collapse, the i=
nvestors want their money back (=E2=80=9Cwe invested in short-term secured =
loans so give us our money=E2=80=9D),=C2=A0the companies don=E2=80=99t want=
 to give it back (=E2=80=9Cyou gave us long-term unsecured loans so let us =
keep the money=E2=80=9D), and everyone is suing. Still it had a certain ele=
gance while it lasted.The arbitrage ramifies everywhere, though. For instan=
ce, if you are doing short-term secured financing of trade receivables and =
securitizing them, it is customary to get an insurer to guarantee the payme=
nts. If you=E2=80=99re just doing long-term secured loans to companies, it =
is less customary. Greensill got the insurance, and here is a story about h=
ow Credit Suisse Group AG, which managed $10 billion of funds that invested=
 in Greensill=E2=80=99s loans, is planning to make claims against Tokio Mar=
ine, Greensill=E2=80=99s main insurer.But=C2=A0how=C2=A0did Greensill get t=
he insurance? Presumably it got the insurance the same way it did everythin=
g else: It created at least a vague impression in the mind of its insurer t=
hat it was actually doing short-term receivables finance. But what did the =
contract actually say? Did it say =E2=80=9Cinsurer will insure any loans ag=
ainst actual invoices,=E2=80=9D or did it say =E2=80=9Cinsurer will insure =
any loans that we make as long as we say=C2=A0the word =E2=80=98receivables=
,=E2=80=99 possibly in connection with the word =E2=80=98prospective=E2=80=
=99 or =E2=80=98future=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D? It is not clear how you=E2=80=99d=
 write that contract, for this novel method of applying words to things, an=
d it matters:The bank=E2=80=99s position is that funding against =E2=80=9Cf=
uture receivables=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 a controversial form of lending offere=
d by Greensill against invoices not yet submitted =E2=80=94 are protected b=
y insurance. Tokio Marine has said publicly only that the insurance =E2=80=
=9Ccovers the accounts receivable of the insured=E2=80=9D.Yeah one of them =
is wrong! I don=E2=80=99t know who, but that is sort of the nature of the G=
reensill arbitrage. If you tell some people that you=E2=80=99re doing short=
-term loans and some people that you=E2=80=99re doing long-term loans someo=
ne is going to end up surprised.


