<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top=
: 30px; margin-bottom: 0;">Silicon Valley insider trading ring!</h2><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CSix Charged in Silicon Valley Insider Tradin=
g Ring=E2=80=9D is the headline on this Securities and Exchange Commission =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24166911.278623/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMS0xMDM/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cBecc37345" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">news release</a>. (There is a related <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24166911.278623/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS=
5nb3YvdXNhby1uZGNhL3ByL3R3by1zb3V0aC1iYXktcmVzaWRlbnRzLWZhY2Utc2VjdXJpdGllc=
y1mcmF1ZC1jaGFyZ2VzLXdoaWxlLXRoaXJkLWRlZmVuZGFudC1wbGVhZHM/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB97910cd8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">criminal case</a>.) It is perhaps less of a Silicon Valley Insider=
 Trading Ring than I had hoped. It=E2=80=99s not, like, senior product mana=
gers at Facebook and Google and Apple all tipping each other, but why would=
 it be. Only two of the six people in the ring worked at tech companies. St=
ill it has its charm:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According=
 to the SEC=E2=80=99s complaint, Nathaniel Brown, who served as the revenue=
 recognition manager for Infinera Corporation, repeatedly tipped Infinera=
=E2=80=99s unannounced quarterly earnings and financial performance to his =
best friend, Benjamin Wylam, from April 2016 until Brown left the company i=
n November 2017. =C2=A0The SEC=E2=80=99s complaint alleges that Wylam, a hi=
gh school teacher and bookmaker, traded on this information and also tipped=
 Naveen Sood, who owed Wylam a six-figure gambling debt. =C2=A0Sood alleged=
ly traded on this information and tipped his three friends Marcus Bannon, M=
atthew Rauch, and Naresh Ramaiya, each of whom also illegally traded on the=
 information. =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">The SEC=E2=80=99s complaint further alleges that Bannon tipped Sood wi=
th material, nonpublic information concerning Bannon=E2=80=99s employer, Fo=
rtinet Inc. =C2=A0As alleged in the complaint, Bannon learned in early Octo=
ber 2016 that Fortinet was going to unexpectedly announce preliminary negat=
ive financial results. =C2=A0Bannon allegedly tipped this information to So=
od, who used it to trade. =C2=A0After learning the information, Sood allege=
dly tipped Wylam and Ramaiya, who also traded.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CHigh school teacher and bookmaker=E2=80=9D is jus=
t an A+ job description. Also I like that the teacher/bookie allegedly pass=
ed some illegal inside information on to a guy who owed him money, so the g=
uy could get the money to pay him back: =E2=80=9CSood owed Wylam a six-figu=
re gambling debt, and Wylam knew that Sood could use profits generated from=
 insider trading to pay off at least part of that debt,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24166911.278623/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2NvbXBsYWludHMvMjAyMS9jb21wLXByMjAyMS0xMDMucGR=
m/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBaba08336" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"it=
emscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">says the SEC complaint</a>. But then Sood got so=
me inside information of his own and allegedly passed it back to his bookie=
/creditor: =E2=80=9CSood also owed Wylam a six-figure gambling debt,=E2=80=
=9D the complaint repeats,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cand Sood expected that, in return =
for providing inside information, Wylam would forgive a portion of the debt=
.=E2=80=9D I don=E2=80=99t know, man, I feel like both of those things can=
=E2=80=99t be true. If Sood could pay Wyman in insider-trading tips, then h=
e shouldn=E2=80=99t be able to pay him off with money from insider trading =
on Wyman=E2=80=99s own tips? The whole economy of insider trading to pay ga=
mbling debts is a little murky to me.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also =
we have=C2=A0talked recently about <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/24166911.278623/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW=
9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMTAvbWF5YmUtZ2FtZXN0b3AtaXMtZ29vZC1ub3c/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cBb190c7bd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;"> insider-trading tradecraft</a>. This is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0not=
 the good tradecraft:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On or aro=
und July 28, 2016, Wylam sent Brown a screenshot of Wylam=E2=80=99s brokera=
ge account, showing the balance after Infinera=E2=80=99s July 27 announceme=
nt, including the profits that Wylam made purchasing Infinera put options b=
efore the announcement. According to Brown, he did a =E2=80=9Cdouble-take=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9Cbecause the number was so big.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Shortly after seeing the screenshot of Wylam=E2=80=99s acco=
unt on July 28, Brown called Wylam on the telephone. During the call, Wylam=
 explained how he made such large profits purchasing Infinera put options b=
efore the July 27 announcement. Brown =E2=80=9Cflipped out=E2=80=9D because=
, in his view, the massive size of Wylam=E2=80=99s trades and profits raise=
d an =E2=80=9Cobvious red flag.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Af=
ter the July 28 call, in order to cover up his role in tipping material non=
public information to Wylam, Brown deleted Wylam from his Facebook account =
and deleted his emails with Wylam. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On A=
ugust 5, 2016, Brown=E2=80=94whose tips enabled his friend, Wylam, to make =
nearly one million dollars=E2=80=94texted his then-girlfriend to inform her=
 that he was going to Wylam=E2=80=99s house to, among other things, =E2=80=
=9Ctalk to him about $.=E2=80=9D One week later, on or around August 12, Br=
own took a photograph of numerous one hundred dollar bills spread across hi=
s bathroom sink.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes yes=
 yes if you have never traded options before, buying a ton of put options j=
ust before a bad earnings announcement does raise an obvious red flag, but =
so does sending your insider buddy a screenshot of your profits! So does ta=
king pictures of the pile of hundred-dollar bills that you got as a payoff =
for your insider-trading tip!=C2=A0</p><h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font=
-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spac=
ing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: =
dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top: 30px; margin-bottom: 0;">Future re=
ceivables insurance</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The more I read about =
Greensill Capital the more impressed I am by the <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24166911.278623/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDMtMTcvZ3JlZW5zaWxsLWRpZG4tdC1qdXN0LWZ=
pbmFuY2UtYmx1ZXN0b25lLXMtc3VwcGx5LWNoYWlu/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb0f8a1d5=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> simple =
arbitrage</a> it pulled off. The core of it seems to be this:</p><ol style=
=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Companies want long-term unsecured loans to fi=
nance their growth: It is safer, for a company, to borrow money for a long =
time, because if you run into trouble you don=E2=80=99t have to pay it back=
. And you=E2=80=99d rather borrow without pledging any specific assets.</li=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Investors want to put their money int=
o short-term secured loans: It is safer, for an investor, to lend money for=
 a short time, because you can always get your money back quickly. And you=
=E2=80=99d rather lend against specific assets that you can seize and sell =
if anything goes wrong.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you can=
 tell companies that they=E2=80=99re getting long-term unsecured funding, a=
nd tell investors that they=E2=80=99re providing short-term secured funding=
, then you=E2=80=99ve got something.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
In broad terms that is not a novel or unique business model. Arguably=C2=A0=
banking<em>=C2=A0</em>works that way: Banks take deposits (short-term loans=
 from investors) and use them to fund long-term loans to companies, so ever=
yone gets what they want;=C2=A0there is a whole apparatus of capital and pr=
udential regulation to make sure that it mostly works out, and there are de=
cades of theorizing about how it works and how it could work better and so =
forth. And there are various forms of shadow banking that also do this sort=
 of =E2=80=9Cmaturity transformation=E2=80=9D: Investors make short-term in=
vestments, companies get long-term financing, and some mumbo-jumbo occurs i=
n the middle to make everyone feel better about it.</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">But Greensill cut through all of this with a much simpler approach=
. Greensill=E2=80=99s innovation was basically to say: Look, if we use term=
s like =E2=80=9Csupply-chain finance=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Creceivables fina=
nce,=E2=80=9D people will <em>think=C2=A0</em>that we=E2=80=99re doing shor=
t-term secured lending because that=E2=80=99s what those terms traditionall=
y mean, but we can just do long-term unsecured lending instead and everyone=
 will be happy. Specifically:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; pad=
ding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Gree=
nsill loaned money to companies in =E2=80=9Creceivables finance=E2=80=9D or=
 =E2=80=9Csupply chain finance=E2=80=9D programs, in which it financed thei=
r accounts receivable (or payable) and got paid back quickly. (That is, the=
 company would sell a product to a customer on credit, Greensill would pay =
the company today, and the customer would pay Greensill back in a month or =
whatever.) But it also cheerfully financed their =E2=80=9Cprospective recei=
vables=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cfuture receivables=E2=80=9D: If a company=C2=A0=
<em>hoped=C2=A0</em>to=C2=A0<em>one day=C2=A0</em>sell some products to som=
e=C2=A0<em>possible future customer</em>, Greensill would lend it money aga=
inst those receivables too. Since those receivables didn=E2=80=99t exist, t=
hose loans would not be paid back quickly, and Greensill would just roll th=
em over indefinitely. For the company this felt like long-term unsecured fi=
nancing: Greensill would give it money, it would invest the money in trying=
 to grow its business, and eventually if the business grew it would pay bac=
k the money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Greensill sold these =
loans to investors emphasizing the words =E2=80=9Creceivables finance=E2=80=
=9D and not so much the words =E2=80=9Cprospective=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cfut=
ure.=E2=80=9D Sure sure sure somewhere in the fine print <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24166911.278623/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQu=
Y29tL2NvbnRlbnQvNDUxYWE2MGQtYjM1ZS00YTcyLTgzN2QtYWNmOGI1N2VjZTRj/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB1348df76" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;"> maybe it mentioned</a> that some of the receivables might n=
ot exist yet, but you put =E2=80=9Csupply-chain finance=E2=80=9D on the cov=
er and sell the loans to money-market-ish funds and nobody really notices.<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Everyone is happy.</li></ol><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nobody is happy now, of course; <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24166911.278623/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb2=
1iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMDYvZ3JlZW5zaWxsLWNhcGl0YWwtZ=
mluYW5jZWQtaW1hZ2luYXJ5LWludm9pY2VzLWZvci1ndXB0YS1zLWxpYmVydHk/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB4cbd4252" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> with Greensill=E2=80=99s collapse</a>, the investors want the=
ir money back (=E2=80=9Cwe invested in short-term secured loans so give us =
our money=E2=80=9D),=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/24166911.278623/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGl=
jbGVzLzIwMjEtMDMtMTcvZ3JlZW5zaWxsLWRpZG4tdC1qdXN0LWZpbmFuY2UtYmx1ZXN0b25lLX=
Mtc3VwcGx5LWNoYWlu/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCb0f8a1d5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the companies don=E2=80=99t wan=
t to give it back</a> (=E2=80=9Cyou gave us long-term unsecured loans so le=
t us keep the money=E2=80=9D), and everyone is suing. Still it had a certai=
n elegance while it lasted.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The arbitrage r=
amifies everywhere, though. For instance, if you are doing short-term secur=
ed financing of trade receivables and securitizing them, it is customary to=
 get an insurer to guarantee the payments. If you=E2=80=99re just doing lon=
g-term secured loans to companies, it is less customary. Greensill got the =
insurance, and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/241=
66911.278623/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvMGNiMDMzODctOWIxNi00ZmQ3LW=
E5OTctNmYzNGQ0YzQ2NThh/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd715e105" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">here is a story</a> about h=
ow Credit Suisse Group AG, which managed $10 billion of funds that invested=
 in Greensill=E2=80=99s loans, is planning to make claims against Tokio Mar=
ine, Greensill=E2=80=99s main insurer.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But=
=C2=A0<em>how=C2=A0</em>did Greensill get the insurance? Presumably it got =
the insurance the same way it did everything else: It created at least a va=
gue impression in the mind of its insurer that it was actually doing short-=
term receivables finance. But what did the contract actually say? Did it sa=
y =E2=80=9Cinsurer will insure any loans against actual invoices,=E2=80=9D =
or did it say =E2=80=9Cinsurer will insure any loans that we make as long a=
s we say=C2=A0the word =E2=80=98receivables,=E2=80=99 possibly in connectio=
n with the word =E2=80=98prospective=E2=80=99 or =E2=80=98future=E2=80=99=
=E2=80=9D? It is not clear how you=E2=80=99d write that contract, for this =
novel method of applying words to things, and it matters:</p><blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bank=E2=80=99s position is that funding agai=
nst =E2=80=9Cfuture receivables=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 a controversial form of =
lending offered by Greensill against invoices not yet submitted =E2=80=94 a=
re protected by insurance. Tokio Marine has said publicly only that the ins=
urance =E2=80=9Ccovers the accounts receivable of the insured=E2=80=9D.</p>=
</blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah one of them is wrong! I don=
=E2=80=99t know who, but that is sort of the nature of the Greensill arbitr=
age. If you tell some people that you=E2=80=99re doing short-term loans and=
 some people that you=E2=80=99re doing long-term loans someone is going to =
end up surprised.</p>
